04530nam a22006495i 9780674028784DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740287847 a10.4159/97806740287842doi  a(DE-B1597)574588  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHQ1090 ǂb B743 2006eb 7aSOC0020202bisacsh04a306.41 aBribiescas, Richard G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMen :bEvolutionary and Life History /cRichard G. Bribiescas. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Chachugi’s Cap -- tPART I. Setting the Stage -- t1. Change Happens -- t2. Birth, Death, and Everything in Between -- t3. The Ancestral Male -- tPART II. Human Male Life History -- t4. Stacking the Deck -- t5. Womb to Grow -- t6. Getting a Life -- t7. Sex and Fatherhood -- t8. The Male Furnace -- t9. Men and Medicine -- t10. The Old Guard -- tConclusion: The Solitary Male -- tREFERENCES -- tILLUSTRATION CREDITS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMales account for roughly 50 percent of the global population, but in America and other places, they account for over 85 percent of violent crime. A graph of relative risk of death in human males shows that mortality is high immediately following birth, falls during childhood, then exhibits a distinct rise between the ages of 15 and 35—primarily the result of accidents, violence, and risky behaviors. Why? What compels males to drive fast, act violently, and behave stupidly? Why are men's lives so different from those of women? Men presents a new approach to understanding the human male by drawing upon life history and evolutionary theory. Because life history theory focuses on the timing of, and energetic investment in, particular aspects of physiology, such as growth and reproduction, Richard Bribiescas and his fellow anthropologists are now using it in the study of humans. This has led to an increased understanding of human female physiology—especially growth and reproduction—from an evolutionary and life history perspective. However, little attention has been directed toward these characteristics in males. Men provides a new understanding of human male physiology and applies it to contemporary health issues such as prostate cancer, testosterone replacement therapy, and the development of a male contraceptive. Men proves that understanding human physiology requires global research in traditionally overlooked areas and that evolutionary and life history theory have much to offer toward this endeavor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Physical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674028784zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674028784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674028784/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK